Introduction¶

The European Soccer Database was analyzed to answer the following questions:

  • What are the distributions of players age, height and weight?
  • What teams improved the most over the time period?
  • Which players had the most penalties?
  • What team attributes lead to the most victories?
  • What are the correlations between players attributes?
  • What is the home team advantage in a soccer match?
  • What are the best teams over the time period?
  • Who are the best players over the time period?
  • Who are the players that improved most over the time period?

The European Soccer Database can be downloaded from Kaggle via the following link: https://www.kaggle.com/hugomathien/soccer. This database contains data for different soccer matches, players, and teams from several European countries from 2008 to 2016. There are 7 tables included: Country, League, Match, Player, Player_Attributes, Team, Team_Attributes.

The soccer database is stored in a SQLite database. To begin with, I will need to first import all the necessary Python libraries for data wrangling and analysis, including sqlite3, numpy, pandas, matplotlib, seaborn.

In [1]:
# first import all the libraries needed

Data Wrangling¶

General Properties¶

In the code cell below, I first used the sqlite3 module to connect to the soccer database file (which is downloaded in the same directory as this Jupyter notebook). Then I used the read_sql() method in pandas to query each of the tables in the soccer database into 7 separate dataframes.

In [2]:
# make separate dataframes for different tables in the soccer database.
soccer = sqlite3.connect('database.sqlite')

df_country = pd.read_sql('SELECT * FROM Country', soccer)
df_league = pd.read_sql('SELECT * FROM League', soccer)
df_match = pd.read_sql('SELECT * FROM Match', soccer)
df_player = pd.read_sql('SELECT * FROM Player', soccer)
df_player_attributes = pd.read_sql('SELECT * FROM Player_Attributes', soccer)
df_team = pd.read_sql('SELECT * FROM Team', soccer)
df_team_attributes = pd.read_sql('SELECT * FROM Team_Attributes', soccer)

Data Cleaning¶

In this section I will show the following data cleaning procedures.

  • Trim columns in the match dataframe that we don't need for future analysis.
  • Convert the data type in either the 'date' or 'birthday' column to datetime.
  • Other data cleaning process shown at the beginning of each question.

Note: I also performed many other data cleaning procedures, such as merging multiple files together to answer specific question listed in the introduction section. For better context for the readers, I moved these procedures to the beginning of each question where you can find them.

From the previous section, we found that there are 115 columns in the match dataframe, and many missing values are present except for the first 11 columns. When we analyze a certain match, we are mostly interested in getting the infomation such as: when the match was played, which two teams played against each other and what the result (how many goals scored by each team) of that match is. Therefore, I decided to keep the first 11 columns because (1): these columns contain the most important information about a match. (2) these columns don't have missing values, which is convenient for further analysis.

In [30]:
# keeping the first 11 columns in the match dataframe, which is equivalent to dropping all columns with missing values
df_match.dropna(axis = 1, inplace = True)

Here are some conclusions for question 0:

  • In terms of birthyear, the oldest player was born in 1967 and the youngest player was born in 1999. The average birthyear of a player is 1986, with most of the players (75%) born after 1983.
  • In terms of players' height, the tallest player is 208.28cm and the shorest player is 157.48cm. The average height of a player is 181.87cm.
  • In terms of players' weight, the heaviest player is 243.00lb and the lightest player is 117.00lb. The average weight of a player is 168.38lb.
  • The birthyear, height and weight are approximately normally distributed. From the birtyear distribution, one can also see that younger players are more favored in soccer games.

Research Question 1: What teams improved the most over the time period?¶

There are many evaluation matrices we can use to measure the improvements of a team, for this question, I decide to investigate the average goals scored by each team in their home and away games, and compare which teams have the most increase in goals from 2008/2009 season to 2015/2016 season.

To answer this question, I realize the most important dataframes are the team and the match dataframes, where we can conncet and inspect the performance of a team in every single game they have played. First, we will need to do some data wrangling with these two dataframes.

In [36]:
# first make a copy of the match dataframe, I will call it match_copy
df_match_copy = df_match.copy()

# merge team and match dataframes, first for the home team
df_match_copy = df_match_copy.merge(df_team, left_on='home_team_api_id', right_on='team_api_id', how='inner')
df_match_copy.rename(columns={'team_long_name': 'home_team_name'}, inplace=True)
df_match_copy.drop(columns=['home_team_api_id', 'team_api_id'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# merge team and match dataframes, next for the away team
df_match_copy = df_match_copy.merge(df_team, left_on='away_team_api_id', right_on='team_api_id', how='left')

df_match_copy.drop(columns=['away_team_api_id', 'team_api_id'], axis=1, inplace=True)

After the data clean process above, I generated a new dataframe match_copy, which contains the home/away team name and goal information. The next steps are:

  • query two subsets from match_copy dataframe, one includes matches only from 2008/2009 season, the other for 2015/2016 season.
  • for each subset, grouy by home/away team names and find their average goals scored.
  • compare the results from both seasons, calculate the difference for each team and list top 10 teams with the most increase in goal scored.
In [38]:
# sub dataframes from match_copy for single season data (2008/2009 and 2015/2016)
df_match_2009 = df_match_copy.query('season == "2008/2009"')
df_match_2016 = df_match_copy.query('season == "2015/2016"')

To add winner info to each match, I created a function that takes home/away team names and goals and outputs the winner's name (or 'Draw') by comparing the goal difference.

In [48]:
# the winner function
def winner(column):
    home_goal, away_goal = column[0], column[1]
    home_team_name, away_team_name = column[2], column[3]
    
    if home_goal > away_goal:
        return home_team_name
    elif home_goal < away_goal:
        return away_team_name
    else:
        return 'Draw'

# create a new column called winner in the match_copy dataframe, which records the winner's name of each match
df_match_copy['winner'] = df_match_copy[['home_team_goal', 'away_team_goal', 'home_team_name', 'away_team_name']].apply(winner, axis=1)

  • In general, a player's overall_rating is positively correlated with his/her potential, with a correlation coefficient of 0.77 (highly correlated), which indicates if a player has a higher potential, it's more likely for him/her to obtain a higher rating.

After checking the match_copy dataframe we created before, I realize it would be easier if we have an extra column, that uses 'home', 'away' or 'draw' to indicate which team won, instead of using the names of the winning teams (in which case we will need to do an extra step and check whether the winner is the home or away team). I decided to create another column named 'home_win_or_away' to store the information I need.

In [66]:
# define a function to generate the winner info: 'home', 'away' or 'draw'
def home_win_or_away(column):
    home_goal, away_goal = column[0], column[1]
    home_team_name, away_team_name = column[2], column[3]
    
    if home_goal > away_goal:
        return 'Home'
    elif home_goal < away_goal:
        return 'Away'
    else:
        return 'Draw'

# add to the match_copy dataframe
df_match_copy['home_win_or_away'] = df_match_copy[['home_team_goal', 'away_team_goal', 'home_team_name', 'away_team_name']].apply(home_win_or_away, axis=1)

# add season info based on date
def add_season(date):
    if date.month >= 7:
        return str(date.year) + "/" + str(date.year + 1)
    else:
        return str(date.year - 1) + "/" + str(date.year)

Conclusions¶

Before I make any conclusions on my analysis on the Kaggle soccer database, I will first talk about its limitations.

  • The match dataframe contains lots of missing values. When I did the analysis, I simply dropped columns with missing values because these rows are also the rows that I'm not interested in. If further analysis is needed on those column, filling missing values or other equivalent methods are necessary.

  • In the player attributes dataframe, I analyzed the scatter matrix between different variables. In order to deal with the missing values, I used column average to fill in those cells. If from other resources these values become available, that dataframe will need to be updated.

  • During the exploration of the relation between different player attributes, I only chose three features because the time it takes to plot all scatter matrix is too long and causes my computer to crush down. if a complete picture is needed, one would include all the features in the corresponding code cell.

To conclude, I have analyzed the Kaggle European Soccer Database using sql, numpy, pandas, matplotlib, LinearRegression, etc.

Here is a summary of the answers to the listed questions:

  • What are the distributions of players age, height and weight?

    • In terms of birthyear, the oldest player was born in 1967 and the youngest player was born in 1999. The average birthyear of a player is 1986, with most of the players (75%) born after 1983.
    • In terms of players' height, the tallest player is 208.28cm and the shorest player is 157.48cm. The average height of a player is 181.87cm.
    • In terms of players' weight, the heaviest player is 243.00lb and the lightest player is 117.00lb. The average weight of a player is 168.38lb.
    • The birthyear, height and weight are approximately normally distributed.

  • What teams improved the most over the time period?

    • In terms of home goal increase per game, Paris Saint-Germain, SL Benfica and Cracovia are the teams that improved most.
    • In terms of away goal increase per game, Sporting CP, Paris Saint-Germain and Rio Ave FC are the teams that improved most.
    • Overall, Paris Saint-Germain is the team that improved the most over the time period, with home goals increased by ~1.6 per game and away goals increased by ~1.2 per game.

  • Which players had the most penalties?

    • Alessio Cerci (4314), Mario Balotelli (4120) and Claudio Marchisio (3984) are the players with most penalties.

  • What team attributes lead to the most victories?

    • Teams with most victories in 15/16 season are Paris Saint-Germain(30), Juventus(29), FC Barcelona(29), SL Benfica(29), FC Bayern Munich(28), Atlético Madrid(28), Real Madrid CF(28), Sporting CP(27), Celtic(26), FC Basel(26).
    • If we take Paris Saint-Germain in 15/16 as a specific example, the most important team attributes are change creation pass and change creation crossing. However, it does not imply this tactic applys to all the teams in different league.
    • Other examples include: For Barcelona, they focused more on their defence aggression and defence team width. For Juventus, they focused more on change creation shooting. For SL Benfica, they focused more on build up play speed.

  • What are the correlations between players attributes?

    • I looked at the correlations between player attributes, in particular, the players overall rating, vision and potential.
    • In general, a player's overall_rating is positively correlated with his/her potential, with a correlation coefficient of 0.77 (highly correlated), which indicates if a player has a higher potential, it's more likely for him/her to obtain a higher rating.

  • What is the home team advantage in a soccer match?

    • Home advantage exists in soccer games, with 45.9% of the matches resulting in home victory, 28.7% of the matches resulting in away victory, 25.4% of the matches ending in a draw.

  • What are the best teams over the time period?

    • The best teams (with the most victories) over the time period are FC Barcelona (234 wins), Real Madrid CF (228), Celtic (218), FC Bayern Munich (193) and Manchester United (192).

  • Who are the best players over the time period?

    • The best player over the time period is Lionel Messi, with an average rating of 92.19.
